atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9963259100914001, "span": {"begin": 1568, "end": 1572}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8270457983016968, "span": {"begin": 1576, "end": 1588}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9982597231864929, "span": {"begin": 1614, "end": 1618}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10966"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "nuclear retinoic acid receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9179226160049438, "span": {"begin": 1649, "end": 1680}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:26536"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "retinoic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9897383451461792, "span": {"begin": 1657, "end": 1670}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5917"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RARs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9831995964050293, "span": {"begin": 1682, "end": 1686}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:4913"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "retinoid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.986470639705658, "span": {"begin": 1722, "end": 1730}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6256"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "RXRs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9924025535583496, "span": {"begin": 1744, "end": 1748}}, {"id": ["mesh:D014212"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atRA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9979777932167053, "span": {"begin": 1755, "end": 1759}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5914"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9968115091323853, "span": {"begin": 1760, "end": 1763}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RXR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9976615905761719, "span": {"begin": 1764, "end": 1767}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "retinoic acid response elements", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5080525875091553, "span": {"begin": 1790, "end": 1821}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:26536"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "retinoic acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9965445399284363, "span": {"begin": 1790, "end": 1803}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RAREs", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.48826202750205994, "span": {"begin": 1823, "end": 1828}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.886456310749054, "span": {"begin": 1842, "end": 1854}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9058622121810913, "span": {"begin": 1914, "end": 1926}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5914"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9990322589874268, "span": {"begin": 1989, "end": 1992}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6256"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "RXRs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9974525570869446, "span": {"begin": 1993, "end": 1997}}], "text": "All-trans retinoic acid (atRA) is the active form of vitamin A/all-trans retinol and is involved in regulating a large number of developmental processes (Bushue &amp; Wan, 2010a; Ghyselinck &amp; Duester, 2019). Although 9-cis RA and 13-cis RA are other metabolic derivatives of vitamin A, atRA is generally considered the primary active metabolite during development, mainly acting as a short-range paracrine signaling molecule (Cunningham &amp; Duester, 2015). atRA exerts dose-dependent effects on morphogenesis, so disruption to atRA concentrations during development can lead to malformations in numerous tissues and organs. During development the spatiotemporal regulation of atRA concentrations in target tissues is tightly controlled by a balance of synthesis and degradation enzymes (Kedishvili, 2013).   Cellular atRA synthesis starts by oxidation of vitamin A to retinaldehyde (RAL) by retinol dehydrogenase-10 (RDH10). RAL is then irreversibly converted to atRA by RAL dehydrogenases (ALDH1A1, ALD1A2, or ALDH1A3). To maintain appropriate retinoid levels in tissues, RAL can be converted back to retinol by enzymatic reactions; further retinoid levels can be controlled by enzymatic degradation of atRA by the cytochrome P450 enzymes CYP26A1, CYP26B1, or CYP26C1, which are differentially expressed throughout the mammalian body (Isoherranen &amp; Zhong, 2019; Shimozono et al, 2013). Inhibition/disruption of any of the enzymes of the atRA synthesis pathway, or increased expression of the atRA degradation enzymes can lead to decreased concentrations of atRA in target cells (Kedishvili, 2013).  The atRA functions as a ligand for the nuclear retinoic acid receptors (RARs), which form heterodimers with the retinoid X receptors (RXRs); the atRA:RAR:RXR complex then binds to retinoic acid response elements (RAREs) upstream of target genes, leading to activation or repression of gene expression in target cells (Chambon, 1996; le Maire et al, 2019). The type and number of RAR/RXRs differ between evolutionary distant animals, but functionally they are all involved in the regulation of development (Gutierrez-Mazariegos et al, 2014).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:52:31 +0000 2026"}